segments.text: Okay, you were giving impressions of Dr. Calhoun.
My relationship with him started in the early 60s.
The Department of Commerce, when I was a guest, the Department of Commerce started what they called an Office of Technical Services, MTS.
And what they would do is they would provide you funding to answer inquiries from industry in your state.
So Dr. Calhoun created at that time what he called the State Technical Services Institute.
And...
He asked me to serve as director of that, which I did.
And so I had some connection with them.
But the real connection, I guess, come with the Sea Grant program down there.
I had quite a hunk of that Sea Grant program at one time.
And that come down there in the late 60s as well, if I remember.
It had to be before 73.
And I did a lot of work with the Sea Grant program.
because I used my industrial economics staff.
It's been perfect.
It'll be all economic studies along the code and things of that nature.
And OTS had gone out of business, by the way.
Off-technical services had gone out of business.
So then I got in on the CGRAT program, and we went all over.
So that's really the period between 65 and 73 is when I got well-acquainted.
make believe that I had never seen John Calhoun, describe him physically and his style.
I wish I had a picture.
I could just give it to you.
Dr. Calhoun was probably the best, the most diversified, intelligent individual that I have ever met in my life.
Dr. Calhoun could grasp things rapidly.
I don't know whether he did a lot of reading on these things before I come in contact with him or not, but I mean, he was always very well versed.
My experience with him was through the State Technical Institute and through the Sea Grant program.
And I always felt that Dr. Calvin was a very easy person to talk to.
I never have seen Dr. Now, some people have seen Dr. Calvin mad.
I've never seen him mad.
Never had in my life.
But we've come pretty close doing those years on different things.
We attended a lot of conferences together.
I did a lot of studies.
And then one day out of the clear blue sky in 1973, on a Thursday afternoon, I was working away, and I got this phone call from Dr. Whitman.

And Dr. Williams said, you know, now, I believe I told you before, I was having my industrial conference start Monday, and I had the governor coming over to get the welcome of press, which I had every year.
And Dr. Williams said, Jim, I'd like to spend a few minutes with you.
And I said, well, that's fine.
I went on down to his office, and after about five minutes of shaking hands, I think he said, you know, we have a vacancy as director of the engineering thinking service.
that we want to create an office of continuing education.
And he said, I'd like for you to get those folks.
Now, tell me about this man, Jack Williams.
Well, of course, Jack Williams and Dr. Calhoun were very close.
I mean, business-wise, I don't know about personal-wise, but they were always there.
They had a lot of respect for each other.
So I said, well, Dr. Williams, I don't know.
I didn't even know them as a thing.
I had a job that I really enjoyed.

getting bigger every day and getting more statewide and that the recognition i said i i'd have to think about a little bit he said well what do you do you need anything to think about i said yes i said i want to talk to you about it i said i want to see what kind of budget they have where their sources of money is coming from so he got on the phone and he called fred benson if i'm not mistaken it might have been calvin but he called somebody
And Tony had been back in office and he said, I'd like you to get some money so I can put in some pension for you.
And so he's done.
How did that happen?
And so we just did a few minutes.
He said, well, when do you think we can get back together?
And I said, we'll get back together Monday morning.
I said, I have all Saturday and Sunday.
We'll get back Monday morning.
So he said, well, just give me a ring Monday morning when you're ready.
And I did.
Some really miscalculated about it, and I didn't get to do it until, we spent it together until about 3 o'clock that afternoon.

But I went there, and I told him what my problem was, and I had, you know, if I could do anything, you know, if I want to do this, I need this, I need this, I need this, I need this, I need this, this, this.
Got down to the bottom line, the most important thing, I had to have total control of all the people in the organization.
And if I was going to be fair with them, if I was going to evaluate each one of them,
But if they didn't fit into the organization, if I'm going to plan for this, then we're going to have to find somebody that will fill that spot.
But anyway, it went on like that.
And I had to listen pretty long.
When I got through, he said, is that all?
I said, yes, sir.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, no, I think he said, you haven't asked for nothing.
You can't get it.
And so I said, OK.
So then he called Fred Benson in California and told him that I'd accepted his job.
As far as you know, he had talked with each of them in depth.
Oh, yes.
Oh, I'm quite sure of that.

I mean, Pastor Williams would have done... No, and another thing I had, see, I had a lot of research projects in that industry, in industrial economics research, and this was in August when he called me in.
And I told him, I said, I couldn't possibly accept a job full of these people.
Because I had sponsors out here that supported me for years.
I said, well, that'd be fun.
That didn't bother any of them.
Describe the extension service when you took over.
What was it?
How big was it?
Where was it?
Well, it was in the old American Legion Hall.
Bob White was before he moved out there.
That used to be just an old building there.
Do you remember that or was it already down when you got here?
I don't know.
Do you remember where the headquarters of Bob White's was until just about a year ago?
No.
Well, you know where the Farmer Student Association building is now?
It used to be that old wooden building right across the street.
Oh, across the street.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Over there by the police station.
Yeah.
Well, I didn't know anybody
I didn't know anybody in Indian Peninsula except Ernie Winochek.
The only reason I knew him, he had more of my in some ways.
And I had met him through Buddy Williams.
And Buddy Williams, you know, he and Ernie were pretty good friends.
But he's the only one I knew.
And so when I took over, they took action at the October 4th meeting.
We'd all been made to motion, Ms. Wilson seconded.
This is 73?
Yes, 73.
I forgot the code.
He said the first 73.
But this meeting was in October before the meeting.
And so when that was announced, it would come out in the paper, and by the day, well, by the way, not the night, you know, the dean of medicine was approved the same day I was approved.
His picture's on the front page of the eagle on one side and mine's on the other.
And I just saw what they fixed, that monument or whatever it was.
But when I went over to the Engineering Extension Service, it had a budget of about $1.5 million, and they had about $50 million.
Where were they based?
All of them here?
Yeah, at that time.
They were a very, I'm not going to say the group, but it's true.
They weren't up-to-date.
There was not an area that you could find that they were up-to-date on.
They taught without lesson plans.
They didn't have any technical manuals.
It's a training organization.
But they have 51 employees and a little over about a million and a half dollars budget.
But their budget, one-third come from Texas Education Agency.
One third comes directly from Appropriations, and then you've got one third of the money from the Seeders.
And that was a third, third, and third.
Well, you've got to realize, the Engineer Potential Service was an overarching section.
And most of the employers were in there since their first job.
Anyway, when it was announced, they had a Dr. Mansfield, who was a social director.
And Deb was the final person that you ever want to meet tomorrow.
But he had been led to believe, either through himself or through Mr. Bearden, see, Mr. Bearden had been director and he retired, that he was going to be the director.
Well, by the way, when I become director, I'm going to be the director.
But anyway, and all of them in the engine and engine service was shocked that he didn't get it.
So the first day I took over, December 1st, 1973, I stayed away from her until I took over.
My wife went in for her third malignancy surgery.
She was operating from that morning, the first day I took over.
Two important events.
Very important events.
I stayed with my wife.
I called Dr. Cowan.
I don't know who I called.
I don't know who I called.
But anyway, they knew where I was at.
And I stayed with her.
call that day, and we were talking to Quade, and we had a doctor out of Houston come up, and that was our third surgery, third emergency surgery.

So after they got through with the surgery, it was in about five hours, Dr. Quade came up and told me, he said, yeah, he said, I don't have much hope for you, and he said that, he said that we're going to
Send her down to Houston, start taking chemotherapy.
No, I'm not going to dwell on this.
Anyway, after the third operation, my wife had about all the operations she wanted.
But anyway, they made an appointment for me to go see this doctor down at the hospital in Houston.
And I got away at the point.
It was 1.30 in the afternoon.
My wife and I walked in.
And I checked in.
He shut the door.
I stayed outside.
And about 20 minutes, or 15 minutes, he come out and said, I'm sorry.
He said, your wife won't let me touch you.
He said, she's not going to take him up there.
And he said, unless I get the exam, they said he's not going to take him.
So we went in.
He said, come on in.
So I told Francis that.
And I said, are you sure you made up your mind?
He said, yep.
I said, how much did it all cost?
He said, $35.
I wrote him a check.
And that was in 1973.
Can you imagine that?
But going back to St. James's.
Where did, primarily geographically, where did, when you took over, where were they doing the instruction that they were?
They were going out in motels.
No, no, but where was it?
Was it in the Houston area?
Oh, it was all over the state.
But it wasn't concentrated in one?
No, no.
Okay.
No, no.
See, they was doing all the training for rural electric co-ops, and their linemen training and things of this nature.
They did a lot of training for the Texas Telephone Association.
But see, they were getting sucked to die.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Right.
Give more examples of that.
Okay.
Law enforcement, all the state and law enforcement, water and wastewater.
They did all the training for water and wastewater in the cities.
Of course, we had the fire protection.
We had the extension part of it, and then we had the fire.
Fireman Training Center was all part of that?
Oh, yeah.
That was the biggest part.
But they used volunteer instructors.
They only had four people on the full-time staff at the farm.
Then they'd go to town, they'd just get somebody at the farm to volunteer.
Was there one client that was by far the key one, the biggest?
Was there?
Well, your rural electric co-op, of course, the organization was so small, they only had 50, 55 people.
But the rural electric co-ops and the Texas Telephone Association
and the water departments of the cities and the law enforcement and the law, those were your, it was all side of the budget.
But to kind of put this thing in perspective, when I left there we had 400 employees and a $39 million budget and was only getting $3 million in general revenue.
$36 million was coming in fees and contracts.
Now wait, give me those numbers again.
When I took over it was
Around 51, I think, employees.
And I left on December, I mean, on January the 31st, 1992.
We had a $39 million budget.
And of that budget, how much did y'all...
The rest you brought in.
All right.
When you started out, you were primarily serving small-town needs...
Rural areas and city water departments in your small town, city water departments, small town lawns.
And the telephone companies were the co-ops.
All right, let's see.
When you took over, were there any key office staff members that you came to rely on?
I'm talking about the people in the office.
I lined them up real fast.
I had to bring him in.
As I told you, Dr. Mansfield was a fine person, and there must have been a shock to his system, because he had never heard of me.
And of course, he just never would.
Well, he had a different philosophy.
His philosophy and my philosophy was completely 100% different.
I was used to the soft money operations.
I've always had the soft money operations.
I liked it.
It gave me a lot of latitude.
They didn't like it.
It was a threat to their jobs.
All right.
When you took over,
In terms of reporting, you reported to?
Dr. Calhoun and Fred Benson.
In which order?
All three of us worked very well.
All right.
On paper, was it to Benson, or was it to both on paper?
Both of them.
Okay.
See, I got funding from Indian Education, Texas Indian University.
All right, let's go back and talk about this man Benson.
He's a Kinson, I think, didn't he come, Kent State, and tell me about his working style and so forth.
Well, you never did leave a meeting with Fred Benson that you didn't know where he stood.
He walked up, he went a bit bashful to pick up the phone and said, Jim, what's this I hear about so-and-so's?
It explained it to him.
That was the end of it, I guess, for me at all.
You know, we had our ground rules set.
I set my ground rules with him, and he said, Calvin, what do you expect?
What kind of report do you want?
What kind of, when do you want me to inform you of something?
Give me some guidelines, because I don't have time to tell you everything I do, and you don't have time to listen to everything I do.
Give me your guidelines.
You know what Mr. Benson's answer was to that?
keep me informed on the matter you think that I could have some input on.
I never called you.
Not that, you know, I just never had a reason.
I can say the same thing about Cal State.
All right, now, officially, the Extension, the Extension, Engineering Extension Service was part of the Texas A&M University and of the system.
No, Engineering Extension Service
was always a part of the system.
All right.
During those years with Williams and Calhoun and Benson, did it matter, system or campus?
Did it matter?
And how you operated?
Not with me.
It didn't matter because I knew exactly what the system was supposed to do.
I knew the policies and procedures of the system.
And I knew what the university was supposed to do.
And I knew exactly what I was expected of me in the university.
And I knew exactly what I was expected of me in the university.
When you wanted to communicate with them
whom did you have to go through to get to Calhoun or to Benson?
Nobody except their secretary.
They all, you always, he had the same, they had the same thing with me.
I mean, we never, I never had one minute that I ever talked.
All right, as you think back on those first years, what were some key decisions that were made by you or anybody else?
Retain to the system.

or pertaining to the work of the of the extension of the extension of the well I'm not being derogatory but I make this statement but I had to have people that would grow I had you know I had maybe two people with college degrees Dr. Mansfield had a degree and then mine had one or two others the rest of them was all non-degree people they had one title it was all called
instructors.

Everybody made the same.
If you're an instructor, you make the same.

But

Day and a half, two days meeting.

And that didn't go too well then.
But anyway, there was a few

But you've got to remember, this was an old organization.
They'd all been in together.
Here's a damn stranger.

They didn't know what management by objective was.
They didn't, you know, it had never been as fun.

The recommendation of Dr. Wigg, she's Fred Benson.
I kept Fred informed on it.
He told me to take it to Dr. Wigg on the pay scale.
And they had about, I'd say they had about $500,000 in the service.
The engineer retention service had about $500,000.
So we automatically, if they had the qualifications, they'd go into this pay status.
If they didn't,
to find somebody that had the qualifications and so forth and so on.
But we'd give them each title, training specialist, associate training specialist, assistant training specialist, you know, to separate them.
But what was the question?
Well, it was about key decisions.
OK. That's how the decisions were made.
And then once we got that thing in line, and unfortunately, the borough got them plans, you know.
He decided to take retirement.
He was about 65 years old.
And he decided to take retirement.
And he took retirement.
Three days later, he died.
He died in the heart attack.
But he didn't bypass her.
So that moved that phase, whatever you want to call it, out.
And then I brought in a new man as associate director.
I brought in Milt Brackett right off.
He was a young engineer.
And how do you spell his last name?
Ratkey, R-A-T-K-E.
He was a young'un.
He was with TTI.
And how did he come about being with us?
TTI was getting into public works training.
Well, I had created a center for public works.
And I picked up the paper one Saturday morning.
There was TTI announcing their public works thing.
So I got a hold of Fred.
I said, Fred, we've got a problem.
And he said, what's the problem?
I told him.
He said, I'll take care of that Monday morning.
So he had Jack Keese in one of those.
In all fact, he'd get out of public work.
That's an extension activity.
That's not a research activity.
And so Milton Rutte was in that position for TPI.
So I just transferred him and one other TPI staff member.
Their whole people worked in public.
And it turned out that Milton was a very, he's a very good engineer, and a very smart individual, and a very, very good writer.
Hard work.
Very hard work.
So I brought him over to the social director.
Well, that made all the rest of the...
I didn't do it by all.
He's there a year, a year and a half.
I observed him for a time.
But that's how that got started.
But when you have to have a decision made, it took me less than five minutes to get it.
I could call Benson.
He'd say, well, what did you do?
Or what do you want to do?
Or I could call Calhoun.
Calhoun wasn't as quick on the draw as Benson was, but he was still very quick.
You know what I mean?
Did you ever get the impression that either one of them ever made a snap judgment without thinking it through?
Let's see, back to other decisions.
Because you're in charge for 19 years?

uh other decisions that you now look back on and say those were key decisions we made well one key decision was made you always build on your strength we had a reputation in the fire all over state we had fire i could contact every legislator with one phone call uh so i said that's our face the first thing i did i put about 150 000 in the fire

Then I said, OK, what's your second turn?
The second strength was electronics, but I had a man in electronics that, you know, had no education, so his name was Artie Patton.
Fine person.

Half-time, September 1st, he'd go to a full-time.
We had it after we had moved to Newark.
And so we then started leaning pretty heavy on electronics, and we got that thing built up.
We had a gentleman and me in the rural electric co-ops.
That was one time, the same gentleman was over at the rural electric co-op training and the Texas Telephone Association training.
So when he retired, I saw that was my strength coming.
In the meantime, I got to be very, very well informed and acquainted with both the people on the Texas Telephone Association board and the electric party.
And they were lobbying for me, the Rural Electric Corps, to take the Indian Amphibian Service with their loggers for funding.
And same thing with Texas Tufts Association.
So I said, well, you know, that's a growth area.

So we started tying them in with TTE.
Started tying in with several others.
Got all their training materials.
TTE had one, five training materials.
They'd give me every bit of their training material that we could use, reproduce.
But at that time, see, none of my people had nothing from training material.
So we got that from the telephone trains, from the telephone.
Then we started getting the power train, electric power.
The real electric co-op didn't have any, but Houston Light and Fire at that time had plenty.
Texas, the big one that really helped me out on my electric training was Texas Fire and Light.
It's now Texas Utility.
So that's how we built the thing.
We took those growth areas.
And then after, you know, we evaluated them, and if they had no growth potential, you know, we'd just say, you know, we may be able to take them out, which we did.
We did away with three or four divisions.
What were they?
Oh, boy.
They were always one-man operations.
We had, well, one thing we did, fire had to have this material.
And I took that directly away from the fire.
I started to have this training, a whole division of it.
But now, currently, we have a very fine guy.
He was a Coast Guard colonel retiring.
He had his master's degree from MIT.
When he retired, we brought him up here with both divisions and also put that under fire.
We did the same thing with management training.
We used to have two levels of management training.
One was for the very bold level training.
So then we just started moving to the higher level, the supervisor training.
So we had to let, so I let that lower division just go and just started what I call supervisor training.
And I'm sure there's five or six others, but I didn't write all of them.
But we ended up, we started out, we had five divisions, and we ended up with 17.
Our staff to  the professionals first is the support staff.
We're about four to one.

And they had to have strong staff people.
But it's about four to one.
Where  in the areas where you all work,
in what area, what work area, subject area, was it easiest to raise money, and which one was most difficult to support?
Well, it was all, there was no difference.
Let me just tell you why.
We started the Senate about 10 years after I got there, about in 78, 79, I put in my first Senate in San Antonio, called South Central Texas Regional Training Center.
And at that time, Henry Cisneros was on the city council, and then Lenny made the mayor's.
Mm-hmm.

The city funded it, and they were totally unhappy with it.

I said, well, this is us.
We've got as much as we want.
I'll go talk to him.
Well, I'll go talk to him.
He was as happy as a lark to get to me.
You can't get along with him.

And so then when we took over South Central Region Training Center, they give us, you know, whenever I did anything like that, you know, I'll give everyone what they need.

We can't rent them.
We don't mean that.
We mean we want facilities built.
If you want anything and things to come in, we have to look the part and play the part.
And so we've got real nice facilities.
The city got it with EDA grant.

So then when they redid the hemisphere area, they wanted us to concentrate on electronics in that area.
So, wow, they built this beautiful big building, you know, right there in the hemisphere.

And before I left, I got two 25-year lease extensions.
So that's 75 years.
But when we put that in, that was our first cylinder.
And when I left that place, we had about a $2 million .

We went all over Arlington.
